# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mariadb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria has been in development since 2007 and was first announced by Michael "Monty" Widenius on his blog.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria is used for internal temporary tables in MariaDB, a community-developed branch of the MySQL database led by Widenius.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria is not shipped with MySQL or Percona Server.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria was initially named "Maria", as a reference to Monty's youngest child.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] It was renamed Aria in 2010 to avoid confusion with the main database it is developed for, MariaDB.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria is very similar to MyISAM, but its purpose is to be a crash-safe alternative to MyISAM.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] Aria does not support foreign keys and, currently, transactions.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] The .frm file contains the table definition (this file exists for all storage engines which write data to disk).
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] PAGE is the only format available for "transactional" tables.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] FIXED and DYNAMIC are the same formats used by MyISAM, and have been mainly implemented for compatibility.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] However, MyISAM's COMPRESSED format is not available in Aria.
[src:mariadb/aria-storage-engine] In order to set the table format, one can use the ROW_FORMAT option in a CREATE TABLE or ALTER TABLE command.
[src:mariadb/documentation] Comprehensive documentation, release notes and learning resources for all MariaDB products.
[src:mariadb/documentation] Start here to set up your environment, connect to your first database and run basic commands.
[src:mariadb/documentation] Dedicated resources for specific MariaDB products and tools.
[src:mariadb/documentation] Stay updated with the latest releases and version-specific changes.
[src:mariadb/innodb] InnoDB became a product of Oracle Corporation after its acquisition of the Finland-based company Innobase in October 2005.
[src:mariadb/innodb] The software is dual licensed; it is distributed under the GNU General Public License, but can also be licensed to parties wishing to combine InnoDB in proprietary software.
[src:mariadb/kb-innodb] Discover InnoDB, the default storage engine for MariaDB Server.
[src:mariadb/kb-innodb] Learn about its transaction-safe capabilities, foreign key support, and high performance for demanding workloads.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB originated as a drop-in replacement for MySQL; the two databases have diverged since version 5.6 in some features, syntax, and behaviour.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Over sixteen years of independent development, MariaDB has evolved into a distinct database with capabilities spanning transactional, analytical, and AI workloads.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The *MariaDB Foundation* is a non-profit organisation that safeguards the open-source development of MariaDB independently of any commercial entity.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] *MariaDB plc* is a commercial entity providing enterprise products, support, and cloud services, owns the MariaDB trademark, and is the largest contributor to MariaDB's codebase.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Michael "Monty" Widenius, one of the founders of MySQL AB and the creator of MySQL and MariaDB, serves as the CTO of both MariaDB Foundation and MariaDB plc.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB is named after founder Michael Widenius' younger daughter, Maria.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MySQL is named after his other daughter, My.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Its logo consists of a sea lion, that Monty Widenius chose based on his encounter with live sea lions while snorkeling with his daughter in the Galápagos Islands.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB was created in 2009 by Michael "Monty" Widenius and other original developers of MySQL, following Oracle Corporation's declaration of an acquisition of Sun Microsystems, which had owned MySQL since 2008.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Concerned that Oracle would restrict MySQL's open-source development, Widenius and co-developers forked the codebase to ensure it remained freely available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The first release, MariaDB 5.1.38, was published on 29 October 2009.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Following Oracle's acquisition, large numbers of the MySQL engineering team left Oracle and joined the MariaDB project through Widenius's company Monty Program Ab.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The company used the Hacking Business Model and was thus co-owned by all the employees.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Early versions used version numbers that mirrored MySQL — 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, and 5.5 — to signal drop-in compatibility.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB published 5.2 and 5.3 releases that MySQL itself skipped.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The primary focus of this period was on improving the optimizer and storage engines: the Aria engine was developed as a crash-safe replacement for MyISAM, and additional engines including FederatedX, OQGraph, and PBXT were introduced or improved.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Wikimedia Foundation migrated Wikipedia's databases to MariaDB in 2013.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Google and Mozilla were also prominent first users.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The first major distribution to ship MariaDB as the default database was openSUSE 12.3 (2013), followed by Fedora 19 later that year.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In 2012, the developers announced that MariaDB would move to a new 10.y.x version series, explicitly signalling that the project was developing independently rather than tracking MySQL releases.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB 10.y.x series, beginning with 10.0 in 2014, established several capabilities that distinguished MariaDB from MySQL, including synchronous multi-master clustering through Galera Cluster and an Oracle compatibility mode enabling PL/SQL stored procedure syntax.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The first long-term support (LTS) release was 10.6 in 2021.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB 11.y.x series began in 2022, with its most significant development being native vector search capabilities introduced in 2024, enabling AI-oriented workloads without requiring a separate extension.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] These became generally available in the 11.8 LTS release in May 2025.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB 12.y.x series began with MariaDB 12.0 in August 2025, introducing a rolling release track alongside the established LTS model.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The series has seen a growing number of outside contributors; the May 2026 releases received contributions from 57 external (non MariaDB plc) contributors.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB 13.0 was released as a preview rolling release in March 2026, with themes including expanded procedural SQL, engine and performance improvements, and enhanced observability.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The release incorporated a notable number of community-contributed pull requests.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB's roadmap is collaboratively shaped by MariaDB plc and community input.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Contributors can propose features or file items directly in the project's JIRA issue tracker.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The two main features that distinguish MariaDB and MySQL from PostgreSQL are the usage of threads instead of processes, and integrated, wide support for replication setups, both local and global.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] This includes geo-distributed replication and multi-master setups via Galera Cluster.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB's API and protocol are compatible with those used by MySQL, including support for native non-blocking operations and progress reporting.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Most connectors, libraries, and applications built for MySQL work with MariaDB.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The official MariaDB connectors are licensed under the LGPL, permitting use in commercial applications without copyleft requirements, and are widely used by OS distributions to connect to both MariaDB and MySQL.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The on-disk format of MySQL and MariaDB were identical up to MySQL 5.7.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MySQL 8.0 changed the on-disk format, including removing the `.frm` schema files, changing the default authentication protocol, and removing and changing several other features, meaning that moving data between MySQL 8.0+ and MariaDB requires a dump and restore.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] All main user-visible features largely share the same syntax, making it relatively straightforward to migrate from MySQL to MariaDB.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Replication between MySQL and MariaDB in both directions remains possible.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Some features diverge further, including GTID replication format and JSON storage implementation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB includes a built-in thread pool in all editions, including the community release, managing connections through a small pool of worker threads rather than a one-thread-per-connection model.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MySQL's thread pool is available only in the commercial MySQL Enterprise Edition.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Oracle compatibility mode (`sql_mode=ORACLE`), available since MariaDB 10.3.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The mode is designed to support incremental migration from Oracle Database, allowing applications to be ported on a per-feature or per-application basis rather than requiring a complete rewrite.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Oracle mode enables PL/SQL stored procedure syntax, Oracle-compatible `NULL` handling, and Oracle-style functions including `NVL()` and `DECODE()`.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In many cases, Oracle applications can be run unchanged with MariaDB by replacing Oracle's ODBC or JDBC connector with the MariaDB connector.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Oracle mode was originally developed in collaboration with DBS Bank.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Sequences, created with `CREATE SEQUENCE`, are first-class database objects independent of any specific table, supporting descending sequences and fine-grained caching control; MySQL has no equivalent `CREATE SEQUENCE` statement.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB provides fully ACID-compliant transactions with support for multiple isolation levels: read uncommitted, read committed, repeatable read, and serialisable.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The default storage engine, InnoDB, implements multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), allowing readers and writers to operate concurrently without blocking each other.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] From MariaDB 11.8, snapshot isolation defaults to strict mode, ensuring transactions see a consistent view of the database from their start time.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports a pluggable storage engine architecture, allowing different engines to be selected per table to match workload requirements — a broader range than the InnoDB-focused default of MySQL.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Beyond storage engines, MariaDB has a set of pluggable APIs.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Plugins can be loaded or replaced at runtime without rebuilding the server.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports analytical workloads through ColumnStore, a columnar storage engine that stores data by column rather than by row, reducing I/O for aggregation queries and making it suited to data warehouse and business intelligence use cases.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Standard SQL analytical capabilities including window functions and common table expressions are supported across all storage engines.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB Enterprise edition from MariaDB plc can use Exasol to speed up analytical queries.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports standard SQL including stored procedures, functions, triggers, views, window functions, and the `JSON` data type with a comprehensive set of document storage and querying functions.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] System-versioned tables, conforming to the SQL:2011 standard, automatically record the complete history of every row.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Historical data can be queried using the `FOR SYSTEM_TIME AS OF` clause to retrieve the state of a table at any past point in time, without manually maintained audit tables or triggers.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The `INSTANT` algorithm for `ALTER TABLE` allows column additions, drops, and default changes to complete in microseconds by updating only metadata, without rebuilding the table.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Since MariaDB 11.2, non-instant schema changes run non-blocking by default, allowing concurrent reads and writes during the operation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports primary-replica replication using a binary log, with asynchronous and semi-synchronous modes.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Multi-source replication allows a replica to receive changes from multiple primary servers simultaneously, and parallel replication reduces lag by applying changes concurrently.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Galera Cluster is a synchronous multi-master replication solution built directly into the MariaDB server, allowing writes to any node while maintaining consistency across the cluster.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports role-based access control, allowing sets of privileges to be assigned to named roles and granted to users, simplifying permission management in large deployments.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Authentication is handled through a plugin architecture supporting multiple methods, including `mysql_native_password`, ED25519 using elliptic-curve cryptography, and PARSEC (Password Authentication using Response Signed with Elliptic Curve), introduced in MariaDB 11.6.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB supports table-level encryption and integration with HashiCorp Vault for key management.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB provides official connectors for C, C++, Java, Python, Node.js, ODBC, and R2DBC, licensed under the LGPL, permitting use in commercial applications without copyleft requirements.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB uses the MySQL client–server protocol, maintaining wire-level compatibility with MySQL client libraries.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB 11.7 introduced a native `VECTOR` data type with HNSW indexing for nearest neighbour search, enabling vector database workloads including retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) without requiring a separate extension or plugin.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The implementation uses SIMD hardware acceleration (AVX2 and AVX512 on x86; NEON on ARM) and became generally available in MariaDB 11.8 LTS in May 2025.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB Vector is integrated with major AI application frameworks including LangChain, LlamaIndex, Spring AI, and LangChain4j.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MySQL Community Edition has supported the `VECTOR` data type since MySQL 9.0 but not vector search indexes.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB version numbers follow MySQL's numbering scheme up to version 5.5.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Thus, MariaDB 5.5 offers all of the MySQL 5.5 features.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] There exists a gap in MySQL versions between 5.1 and 5.5, while MariaDB issued 5.2 and 5.3 point releases.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Since specific new features have been developed in MariaDB, the developers decided that a major version number change was necessary.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB Foundation is a non-profit organisation founded in December 2012 to oversee and safeguard the open-source development of the MariaDB database server, independently of any commercial entity.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation is incorporated in Delaware, USA, and is funded through corporate and individual sponsorships, with MariaDB plc being the primary code contributor.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Its work is guided by three core principles: openness of the codebase to contributions based on technical merit, increasing adoption of MariaDB across users and platforms, and ensuring long-term continuity of the project independently of commercial interests.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In December 2012, MySQL Ab founders Michael Widenius, David Axmark, and Allan Larsson announced the formation of the MariaDB Foundation to oversee the development of MariaDB, which had been forked in 2009 from MySQL.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] At the time of founding, the Foundation aimed to establish a governance model similar to that of the Eclipse Foundation, and appointed the Eclipse Foundation's Executive Director Mike Milinkovich as an advisor to lead the transition.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Simon Phipps became the Foundation's first CEO in April 2013 but resigned in 2014 when the MariaDB trademark was transferred to SkySQL (later renamed MariaDB Corporation Ab).
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation's first formal sponsor was MariaDB plc (then known as MariaDB Corporation Ab), which joined in 2014 after initial agreements on the division of roles between the Foundation and the Corporation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The MariaDB trademark is owned by MariaDB plc and used under licence by the Foundation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In 2013, Google tasked one of its engineers to work at the Foundation, reflecting early industry support for the project.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Otto Kekäläinen served as CEO from January 2015 to September 2018.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Eric Herman, a developer at Booking.com and former MySQL and Sun employee, joined the Foundation board in May 2015 and was elected Chair in November 2016.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Arjen Lentz was briefly appointed CEO in October 2018 before leaving in December 2018.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Kaj Arnö joined as CEO on 1 February 2019.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In October 2020, the Foundation began publishing its board meeting minutes openly by default.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In December 2021, the board declined to create a Diamond Sponsorship tier that would have granted MariaDB Corporation the right to block other sponsors, affirming the Foundation's operational independence from its primary commercial supporter.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] A significant change in the MariaDB ecosystem came in December 2022, when MariaDB plc listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In 2024 K1 Investment Management completed an acquisition of the company taking it private.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] At the time, the Foundation strengthened its own governance: in November 2023, the board formalised safeguards including limiting any single corporation to one direct board seat and requiring a supermajority vote for changes to the Foundation's mission.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Arnö later reflected that the preceding years had been challenging for the Foundation's relationship with MariaDB plc, and that the arrival of new management had restored positive dynamics.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Following the change of ownership, the Foundation and MariaDB plc began rebuilding their working relationship, conducting shared strategy sessions around cooperation and openness.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Kaj Arnö served as CEO until February 2025, when he was elected Chairman of the Board and became Executive Chairman, succeeding Eric Herman, who had served as Chair since November 2016.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Anna Widenius was confirmed as CEO at the same time.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation also signed a Memorandum of Understanding with MariaDB plc in 2025, formally recognising it as the Primary Code Contributor for 2022–2024.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation states that its staff contribute to MariaDB Server through feature design, code review, documentation, and porting and packaging across platforms, and that it works to assist new contributors to the project.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] It promotes MariaDB at conferences and through community engagement.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation publishes board meeting minutes and financial reports.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Technical decisions are made by contributors through open mailing list discussions, with the board responsible for organisational strategy.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation organises a range of community events.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB Server Fest is a recurring developer-focused event series held in multiple cities across Europe, Asia and the Americas, sometimes co-located with major open-source events such as FOSDEM in Brussels, Belgium.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The Foundation organises its sponsors into tiers.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Diamond sponsors include Amazon and DBS; Platinum sponsors include IBM, Intel, and MariaDB plc; and Gold sponsors include more than 30 organisations, among them Hetzner, IONOS, Automattic, and Nextcloud.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In addition to financial sponsorship, some sponsors contribute directly to the codebase.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Amazon has become one of the largest code-contributing corporations outside MariaDB plc, including contributions to MariaDB Vector.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB plc (formerly MariaDB Corporation Ab) is a database software company and the primary contributor to the MariaDB database server.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] It develops the MariaDB Enterprise Platform, database connectors, and MariaDB Cloud, a cloud database service.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The company is headquartered in Silicon Valley and Dublin, Ireland, and has been privately owned by private equity firm K1 Investment Management since September 2024.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The company was founded in 2010 as SkySQL Corporation Ab by Patrik Backman, Ralf Wahlsten, Kaj Arnö, Max Mether, Ulf Sandberg, Mick Carney, and Michael "Monty" Widenius.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] It merged with Monty Program Ab on 23 April 2013.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] On 1 October 2014 the combined entity was renamed MariaDB Corporation Ab to reflect its role as the main driving force behind the development of MariaDB Server.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB Corporation was funded with a combined total of approximately $123M across A-series (2012), B-series (2013–2016), and C-series (2017–2022) funding rounds.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] A-series investors included OpenOcean and Tesi (Finnish Industry Investment Ltd).
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The B-series was led by Intel, which invested $20M in 2013.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In January 2016, Michael Howard was named CEO, with Michael Widenius continuing as CTO.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The C-series was led by Alibaba with a $27M investment in 2017, alongside a €25M loan by the European Investment Bank.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In March 2020, MariaDB Corporation launched SkySQL, a database-as-a-service (DBaaS) built on the MariaDB Enterprise Platform and hosted on Google Cloud Platform.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The offering combined transactional and analytical workloads—including distributed SQL and columnar storage—in a single managed cloud service, distinguishing it from competing hosted offerings such as Amazon RDS and Microsoft Azure's MariaDB service.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The share price declined sharply in the years that followed.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In October 2023, the company restructured, discontinuing its SkySQL cloud database service and laying off staff.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] SkySQL was spun off as an independent company in December 2023.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In September 2024, K1 Investment Management completed a tender offer for all outstanding shares for approximately $37 million, taking the company private and appointing Rohit de Souza as CEO.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] The new management subsequently worked to rebuild the company's relationship with the open-source community, including the MariaDB Foundation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] In August 2025, MariaDB plc reacquired SkySQL.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB plc contributes to MariaDB Server and develops the MariaDB database connectors (C, C++, Java, Node.js, ODBC, Python, R2DBC) licensed under the LGPL, allowing use in commercial applications without the copyleft requirements of MySQL's GPL connectors.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] MariaDB is the default database in many of the major Linux distributions and several BSD operating systems, having replaced MySQL as distributions adopted it through the 2010s.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Beyond Linux and BSD, the OpenSolaris-derived OpenIndiana has used MariaDB as its default MySQL provider since 2013.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] As of September 2025, MariaDB is used by more WordPress installations than MySQL, accounting for 54% of WordPress database deployments according to official WordPress statistics.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Drupal lists MariaDB as its recommended database for Drupal 10, 11, and 12 in its official documentation.
[src:mariadb/mariadb] Nextcloud recommends MariaDB over MySQL in its official administration manual.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Explore the core concepts of MariaDB standard replication.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Learn about the primary-replica architecture, data redundancy strategies, and how to scale read operations effectively.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] In MariaDB 11.8, the default character set and collation have changed.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] This has implications on replicating to older replicas, particularly replicas running MariaDB 10.6 or older.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] See for details, and how to configure MariaDB 11.8+ primaries to replicate to older replicas.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Replication is a feature allowing the contents of one or more servers (called primaries) to be mirrored on one or more servers (called replicas).
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] You can exert control over which data to replicate.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] All databases, one or more databases, or tables within a database can each be selectively replicated.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] The main mechanism used in replication is the .
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] If binary logging is enabled, all updates to the database (data manipulation and data definition) are written into the binary log as binlog events.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Replicas read the binary log from each primary in order to access the data to replicate.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] A is created on the replica, using the same format as the binary log, and this is used to perform the replication.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Old relay log files are removed when no longer needed.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] A replica server keeps track of the position in the primary's binlog of the last event applied on the replica.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] This allows the replica server to re-connect and resume from where it left off after replication has been temporarily stopped.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] It also allows a replica to disconnect, be cloned and then have the new replica resume replication from the same primary.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Primaries and replicas do not need to be in constant communication with each other.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] It's quite possible to take servers offline or disconnect from the network, and when they come back, replication will continue where it left off.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] Replication is used in a number of common scenarios.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] The following table describes replication compatibility between different MariaDB Server versions.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] In general, the replica should be of the same or a later version.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] provided the configurations for each server allow for consistent behavior in the execution of the events (i.e. the execution of the event should not be reliant on newer configuration variables, character sets/collations, etc, that don't exist on the replica).
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] See for more details on unsafe statements.
[src:mariadb/replication-overview] For replication compatibility details between MariaDB and MySQL, see .
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Understand MariaDB Server's storage engines.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Explore the features and use cases of InnoDB, Aria, MyISAM, and other engines to choose the best option for your specific data needs.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] An introduction to MariaDB's pluggable storage engine architecture, highlighting key engines like InnoDB, MyISAM, and Aria for different workloads.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] A guide to selecting the appropriate storage engine based on data needs, comparing features of general-purpose, columnar, and specialized engines.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The Archive storage engine is optimized for high-speed insertion and compression of large amounts of data, suitable for logging and auditing.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Learn about the Aria storage engine in MariaDB Server.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Understand its features, advantages, and use cases, particularly for crash-safe operations and transactional workloads.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The BLACKHOLE storage engine discards all data written to it but records operations in the binary log, useful for replication filtering and testing.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The main characteristic of CONNECT is to enable accessing data scattered on a machine as if it was a centralized database.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The CSV storage engine stores data in text files using comma-separated values format, allowing easy data exchange with other applications.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] FederatedX is a storage engine that allows access to tables on remote MariaDB or MySQL servers as if they were local tables.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The MEMORY storage engine stores tables in RAM for fast access, but data is lost upon server restart.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] The MERGE storage engine allows a collection of identical MyISAM tables to be treated as a single logical table, useful for managing large datasets.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Mroonga (formerly named Groonga Storage Engine) is a storage engine that provides fast CJK-ready full text searching using column store.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Explore the MyISAM storage engine in MariaDB Server.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Understand its characteristics, including suitability for read-heavy workloads, and its role in specific use cases.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Learn about the MyRocks storage engine in MariaDB Server.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Discover its advantages for flash storage, high write throughput, and compression efficiency in modern database deployments.
[src:mariadb/storage-engines] Explore the OQGRAPH storage engine in MariaDB Server.
